  "text": "Returning to the example of the wine-buying customer mentioned in the introduction, we propose that she would judge the same price to be less expensive if she encountered it in a discount wine store (low price image) than if she were to find it in a specialty wine store (high price image). This prediction is conceptually consistent with some early work on price image, which suggested that consumers can use a price image heuristically to evaluate prices [CITATION_1] . Price image theories are by no means consistent on this point, however. Others have argued that price image influences only a consumer's choice of stores, but not the evaluation of individual shelf prices [CITATION_2] .",
